content: I buy a redial app for a reason. Unemployment number is always busy. Redial app doesn't help. Was expecting it to redial after x amount of time for busy signal.
replyContent: I'm sorry but no app can do what you want. The Android API does not provide a way to detect a busy signal, so it is basically impossible to currently implement that functionality. Some other apps implement a timer to auto cancel a call, but that has the risk of cancelling a successful call.

content: Very inconsistent. Tried it 4 different times throughout the day. Only 1 time did it actually hang up and redial on its own. The other times I had to hang up the call myself. Also did not put phone on speaker except the time that it actually redial on it's own.
replyContent: Hi, the behavior you are describing matches exactly the description of the app: It cannot detect a busy signal, and therefore you may have to hang up yourself upon a busy signal. Sometimes the network itself disconnects automatically, but that is beyond the app's control. The speaker is intentionally activated a few seconds after a dial attempt.

content: Speaker wasnt automatically so you have to press that button anyway
replyContent: Hi Don, the speaker has a bit of an intentional delay, so that it only triggers when the call goes through.

There are two ways to stop the redial. One is to go back to the app (via e.g. the back button) and there you can click the red button to cancel the redial. Another way is to cancel it via the notifications, because there should be one that cancels the redialing. Could you please try them and please tell us if these solutions work?
